{panel:title=Atlassian Update - 30 may 2018|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ebf2f9|titleBGColor=#ebf2f9|bgColor=#ffffff}
Hi everyone,

I'm proud to announce that with Jira [7.10|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftware/jira-software-7-10-x-release-notes-949226697.html] we have shipped [Archiving Projects for Jira Data Center|https://www.atlassian.com/blog/jira-software/project-archiving-jira-software-enterprise]. Now DC admins can easily archive and restore projects together with their issues.

Regards,
 Jakub Kurcek
 Product Manager, JIRA Platform
{panel}
*Original description:*
It should be possible to put a project into a 'held' state, where nothing can be done to it, or a 'hidden' state so it does not show up in the non-admin web interface.

I'm sure other states would be useful to others too.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1431].
  {panel}



*Original request description:*
 
Currently, I need to give my project manager the jira-administor permission in order for him to create new projects. Unfortunately, this opens up the possibly of him doing other stuff, like changing the mail server. Not that he would, but when you give permissions...
Suggestion: Make Create New Project a separate global level permission.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1423].
  {panel}

An option to automatically set "Estimated Time Remaining" to 0 when an issue is closed would be very useful. Combined with other requests such as keeping the original estimate, and reports on late tasks and time remaining I think this would make a lot of sense.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1391].
  {panel}

*Original request description:*
 
As a JIRA administrator I am responsible for managing a large installation with multiple users and groups. Given the dynamic nature of my environment it is very difficult for me to create the correct user group name which can be used for many projects later on. I need to be able to rename the user groups, to reflect the changes my organisation undergoes.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1390].
  {panel}

When granting permissions to a project, it would be great to choose more than one group at a time.  Currently radio buttons are being used, what about checkboxes?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1375].
  {panel}

Can you please provide support for mandatory fields for both custom and predefine fields.  It'll be even better if there is a customizable validation framework that user/tester can specify (something along the regular expression line?) so that they don't have to depends on their developer peer to cutomize it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1357].
  {panel}

Often I want to see the issues relating to the next issue to be released.  Similar to the dashboard, we should be able to sort and save filters on the next released version.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-1352].
  {panel}

At the moment there is no way to reset the admin password apart from going to the database.

JIRA should have a command line jar that allows the resetting of admin passwords.  eg:

java -jar passwordReset.jar -userName admin -newPassword password
